Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The chromosome continuously gets smaller with each replication. This shortening occurs on the 5 prime end of the DNA. Thus creating a hang over of the 3 prime end. Each daughter strand with have this 3 prime hang over. Telomeres prevent the loss of the entire DNA when shortening occurs.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Observing various specialized drosophila chromosomes and the mutations that occur in them. This enabled us to more easily identify the locations of certain genes. This greatly enhanced our understanding of our own gene locations by developing techniques to identify gene locations.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Euchromatic is a lightly packed form of chromatin and usually has a high concentration of genes present. However, it is not always active due it constantly undergoing active transcription. Heterochromatic regions are tightly packed forms of DNA. These are important in regards to expression of genes. There are two important varieties of heterochromatin constitutive and facultative. One is involved in silencing genes and the other involved in gene expression or repression signals.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] This concept relates to an extremely important biological phenomena encountered numerous times before which is DNA replication. One of the most important concepts in biology it is important to understand to completion how our DNA is replicated. In understanding we can understand a variety of diseases and understand how our bodies work. In knowing that linear chromosomes with telomeres create problems during replication can help us understand this phenomenon to completion.
phenomenonB Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonB[comment] Chromosomes contain our genes and understanding the varying parts of the chromosome, euchromatic and heterochromatic, are important in understanding gene expression. These different components play important roles in what is silenced and what is expressed.
groupTime451 2263.63

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] After DNA replication, each newly synthesized DNA strand is shorter at its 5' end than at the parental DNA strand's 5' end. This shorter end causes a hangover in the 3' region of each of the daughter DNAs. Special structures at the end of chromosomes called telomeres prevent the entire loss of the DNA strand, caused from the shortening. These structures help protect important genes from being deleted such as in the linear chromosomes case.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Specialized chromosomes in drosophila allowed the identification of gene locations because we could observe different mutations in the specialized chromosomes and it helped in distinguishing the location of genes by observing these mutations.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] There are different varieties of chromatid. They are distinguished by the intensity of staining regions. The lighter stained areas are euchromatic in comparison to the dark staining region which are associated with heterochromatic regions. These areas are darker due to the heterochromatic having more tightly packed DNA. Heterochromatic regions are responsible for gene regulation and protection of chromosomal integrity. Whereas, euchromatic is gene rich and is under active transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Eukaryotic organisms have much more DNA than in comparison to prokaryotic organisms. In prokaryotes, replication occurs in the cytoplasm and has only one point of origin. However, in eukaryotes replication occurs in nucleus and has multiple points of origin. Replication for prokaryotes happens at much faster rate. In addition, eukaryotes have a specialized replication process for the telomeres at the end of the chromosomes and prokaryotes do not.

groupTime450 24.26

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Telomeres are repetitive DNA sequences on the end of linear chromosomes. Because of DNA polymerase requiring a primer to initiate replication, the telomeres will shorten every time a cell divides. Eventually there will be no room for the primer at the 3' end of the DNA, meaning that part of the telomere is lost every division.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Polytene chromosomes found in larvae of flies can be seen in the nuclei of interphase cells. When seen under a light microscope, a series of bands were seen. Although it is not known how many genes are contained in each band, gene activity creates a "puff" on the chromosome, allowing its location on a band to be found.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The chromosome is not structurally uniform - some parts of the chromosome remain condensed during interphase. These parts stain and are called heterochromatin. Euchromatin, on the other hand uncoil during interphase. This region is only lightly stained. Heterochromatic regions are inavtive because they lack genes or contain repressed genes. Examples of heterochromatic regions are the telomeres and centromeres.
phenomenonA Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonA[comment] Heterochromatic regions such as the centromere and telomere do not code proteins, but aid the structure and movement of the chromosome.
phenomenonB Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonB[comment] "Immortal" cells get around telomere loss by using telomerase, an enzyme that adds telomeric repeats to the 3' end of the DNA using its own RNA component as a template.
groupTime451 3033.98

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand how the fact that DNA polymerase needs a primer in eukaryotes means that telomeres will shorten over time. I also understand how telomerase will add telomeric repeats to the 3' end of the DNA, allowing the telomeres on the new DNA to have a normal length.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand how polytenes can display gene locations on their visible bands. I understand how their size comes from the many replications that the DNA undergoes without division or separation. I also understand how "puffs" uncoiling in a band can disclose the location of a specific gene.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand how condensed heterochromatin will be heavily stained and how uncondensed euchromatin will be lightly stained. I understand that heterochromatin is non-coding or repressed genes, that remains coiled during interphase, unlike euchromatin.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand how DNA replication will differ in prokaryotes versus eukaryotes. In prokaryotes, it occurs in the cytoplasm, there is only one origin of replication, only two replication forks are formed, and it is very fast. In eukaryotes, it occurs in the nucleus, there can be multiple origins of replication (meaning there can be multiple replication bubbles), and it is slower than replication in prokaryotes.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] When RNA primers are removed from the lagging strand, it leaves a gap at the 3' end that can't be filled immediately. This problem is solved by the enzyme telomerase. This enzyme has a RNA template that recognizes the G-T rich telomere region at the end of the DNA and starts to elongates the parental strand of the DNA. Then RNA primers come in to fill the original gap in the lagging strand.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The light staining regions are exon and the dark staining regions are introns.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] After every DNA replication, some telomere sequences are lost at the 5' end of the newly synthesized strand of DNA, but because these are noncoding sequences, their loss doesn't effect the cell. However, these sequences are not unlimited; eventually after several replications, all the telomere repeats are lost, and the DNA risks losing coding sequences with further replications.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Polytene chromosomes are rarely found in eukaryotes. However, these chromosomes are found in various tissues in Drosophila and most flies. They can be seen under light microscopy and can be viewed in nuclei interphase cells.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Euchromatin in chromosomes is uncoiled and active. Where as heterochromatin is coiled tightly and mostly inactive.
phenomenonA Specialized Drosophila chromosomes allowed the identification of gene locations.
phenomenonA[comment] Bulges in DNA where it has uncoiled are called puffs. These represent areas of high gene activity where RNA is being transcribed.
phenomenonB Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonB[comment] Telomeres are actually there to protect chromosomes from degrading but after several replications DNA can become at risk of losing valuable coding regions.

groupTime450 21.9

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] DNA polymerase can only synthesize a new strand of DNA as it moves along the template strand in the 3' –> 5' direction. This works fine for the 3' –> 5' strand of a chromosome as the DNA polymerase can move uninterruptedly from an origin of replication until it meets another bubble of replication or the end of the chromosome. However, synthesis using the 5' –> 3' strand as the template has to be discontinuous. When the replication fork opens sufficiently, DNA polymerase can begin to synthesize a section of complementary strand — called an Okazaki fragment — working in the opposite direction. Later, a DNA ligase stitches the Okazaki fragments together.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In Drosophila, the role of telomerase is carried out by three specialized retrotransposable elements, HeT-A, TART and Tahre. Telomeres contain long tandem head-to-tail arrays of these elements. Within each array, the three elements occur in random, but polarized, order. Some are truncated at the 5′ end, giving the telomere an enriched content of the large 3′ untranslated regions which distinguish these telomeric elements from other retrotransposons.
explainConcepts[SQ003] There are two varieties of chromatin. They are euchromatin and heterochromatin. These two forms are distinguished in a cytological manner dealing with how intensely each form is stained. The euchromatin is less intense than heterochromatin. This only indicates that heterochromatin has tighter DNA packaging. To find out more about the difference between euchromatin and heterochromatin, this article will provide you a quick look regarding these two chromatin forms.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] DNA polymerase can only synthesize a new strand of DNA as it moves along the template strand in the 3' –> 5' direction. This works fine for the 3' –> 5' strand of a chromosome as the DNA polymerase can move uninterruptedly from an origin of replication until it meets another bubble of replication or the end of the chromosome. However, synthesis using the 5' –> 3' strand as the template has to be discontinuous. When the replication fork opens sufficiently, DNA polymerase can begin to synthesize a section of complementary strand — called an Okazaki fragment — working in the opposite direction. Later, a DNA ligase stitches the Okazaki fragments together.
phenomenonB Specialized Drosophila chromosomes allowed the identification of gene locations.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] DNA polymerase can only synthesize a new strand of DNA as it moves along the template strand in the 3' –> 5' direction. This works fine for the 3' –> 5' strand of a chromosome as the DNA polymerase can move uninterruptedly from an origin of replication until it meets another bubble of replication or the end of the chromosome. However, synthesis using the 5' –> 3' strand as the template has to be discontinuous. When the replication fork opens sufficiently, DNA polymerase can begin to synthesize a section of complementary strand — called an Okazaki fragment — working in the opposite direction. Later, a DNA ligase stitches the Okazaki fragments together.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] In Drosophila, the role of telomerase is carried out by three specialized retrotransposable elements, HeT-A, TART and Tahre. Telomeres contain long tandem head-to-tail arrays of these elements. Within each array, the three elements occur in random, but polarized, order. Some are truncated at the 5′ end, giving the telomere an enriched content of the large 3′ untranslated regions which distinguish these telomeric elements from other retrotransposons.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] They are euchromatin and heterochromatin. These two forms are distinguished in a cytological manner dealing with how intensely each form is stained. The euchromatin is less intense than heterochromatin. This only indicates that heterochromatin has tighter DNA packaging. To find out more about the difference between euchromatin and heterochromatin, this article will provide you a quick look regarding these two chromatin forms.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] it occurs inside the cytoplasm, only one origin of replication per DNA molecule, origin of replication of about 100-200or more nucleotides

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] After new DNA has been synthesized, the RNA primers are removed, which leaves gaps in the DNA. In the middle of the DNA strand, the gaps are easily filled because the DNA polymerase can use the newly synthesized DNA upstream from the gap as a landing pad, so to speak. At the end of a linear strand of DNA, however, there is no such framework upstream. Therefore, the structure of the telomere must support an alternative method for synthesizing DNA at this point.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Drosophila have polytene chromosomes, which exhibit unique banding patterns when viewed under a light microscope. The polytene chromosome itself is actually several copies of the same DNA strand, which reside side-by-side, thus producing the banding effect. Each band represents a specific gene located at that point on all of the individual strands of DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ003] All chromosomes have euchromatic regions and heterochromatic regions when they are in chromatin form. Euchromatic regions stain very lightly and carry the DNA that is used for active transcription. Essentially, this is where all of our active DNA is located. Heterochromatic regions, on the other hand, stain very darkly and carry inert, non-coding DNA.
phenomenonA Specialized Drosophila chromosomes allowed the identification of gene locations.
phenomenonA[comment] Specific gene sites can be seen in the banding pattern of polytene chromosomes, and puffs around those chromosomes represent high gene activity.
phenomenonB Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonB[comment] Just by staining chromatin with a certain stain, we can see where the transcribing DNA is and where the centromere/telomere are.
groupTime451 302.01

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that in 5’ to 3’ DNA replication, the repeated use of RNA primer leaves gaps in the newly synthesized strand of DNA. I also understand that after the primer is removed, the gaps in the middle of the DNA strands are filled; however, the gaps at the 5’ end of the DNA strand remain unfilled. This is where the enzyme telomerase steps in. Telomerase has an RNA component that aligns with the over-hanging telomere of the 3’ strand of DNA. Through reverse transcription, the RNA then attracts base pairs and synthesizes more DNA on the telomere, moving further away from the double helix as it does so. Telomerase then releases from the DNA, allowing primase and DNA polymerase to fill the gap. After the gap is filled, the primer is removed and DNA ligase seals the gap.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that Drosophila, as well as some other flies, protozoa, and plants, have polytene chromosomes, which are large, irregularly shaped chromosomes. I understand that they are large because each chromosome is actually a series of replicated DNA strands that have remained side-by-side. When viewed under a light microscope, polytene chromosomes exhibit banding patterns, and each band appears to be associated with individual genes. I understand that this view is strengthened by the appearance of “puffs”, or small bulges, that occur when the gene is being transcribed into RNA. The chromosome puffs outward a bit as it is uncoiled for RNA transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that the terms euchromatic and heterochromatic apply to DNA when it is chromatin. I understand that euchromatin houses DNA that is actively transcribed and therefore genes that are actively expressed. Heterochromatin, by contrast, carries non-coding DNA in the form of no genes or genes that are repressed. I understand that the telomere and centromere regions of the chromatid are composed of heterochromatin and are good examples of how non-coding DNA can still serve a useful purpose. I also understand that heterochromatin only occurs in eukaryotes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that prokaryotes and eukaryotes have many differences in DNA replication. For example, prokaryotic DNA is circular, while eukaryotic DNA is linear. This means that there is only one origin of replication in prokaryotes, because the DNA polymerases can simply go all the way around the circle. In eukaryotes, however, there are many origins of replication because the DNA strands are so much larger—it would simply take too long to copy the DNA from one spot. The Okazaki fragments on the lagging strand are also smaller in eukaryotes because the nucleosomes must be moved. I understand that eukaryotes have telomeres at the end of the linear DNA strand which allow the gap left by the RNA primer to be filled.

explainConcepts[SQ001] When linear chromosomes replicate, the RNA primer at the 5' end of the new strand is removed but the bases are not replaced. This leads to an incomplete 5' strand and a 3' overhang. Telomeres are at the ends of chromosomes and consist of a series of noncoding bases repeated hundreds of times. The DNA undergoes many rounds of replication but without strand separation of cytoplasmic division. Polytenes have bands on them and this is a visible manifestation of genes.

Nucleosomes must be moved for replication to proceed and the rate of copying DNA is about 25X less in Eukaryotes. Eukaryotes have telomeres and special enzymes which extend telomeres during replication.

No problem occurs in DNA replication for the leading strand since DNA polymerase can synthesize the entire strand easily. But the problem occurs in lagging strand in which small fragments are formed due to RNA primer being attached to the DNA strand which allows the DNA polymerase to synthesize the other strand. However, in the end, the problem is that there is no place or not enough base pair for the RNA primer to attach so that the DNA polymerase cannot attache and thus so the DNA gets smaller and smaller after each cell division.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] DNA replication, consisting of transcription from DNA to RNA and of translation from RNA to proteins, varies from eukaryotes, where the process is more complicated, to prokaryotes where the process is relatively more simple. Prokaryotic transcription involves only one origin of replication, where eukaryotic transcription has multiple origins in order to facilitate quicker transcription of increased genetic material. Additionally, and very significantly, eukaryotic replication consists of RNA post transcriptional modification such as the addition of a 5' cap and a poly A tail that aid in the lifespan and recognition by other receptors of the RNA molecule.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Chromosomes have ends called telomeres that are very important to the functioning of the chromosome. Special enzymes called telomerases are involved in lengthening the telomeres so that the chromosome does not get any shorter. Telomeres are difficult to copy, but they are so important because the telomeres keep the chromosome from getting any shorter.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Polytene chromosomes of Drosophila have allowed us to identify gene locations because the chromosomes are very easy to see and read. They have chromosome puffs, which are areas of RNA transcription, which allow us to see the different genes. When the DNA is unwound at this time, it is easy to see the genes, thus we can see their locations on the chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The euchromatic areas, where much transcription occurs, is important to the chromosome because it is the part of the chromosome that is important to copy for the next cells. Heterochromatic areas, where essentially no transcription occurs is also important because these areas start and end transcription. Without these areas, transcription would not occur. The TATA and CAT box are in this area and they help transcription to begin.

groupTime450 22.11

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] In DNA replication, DNA polymerase has to have something to “hold on” to. This need is resolved with the use of RNA primers that will go a few base pairs away from the area of DNA that will be synthesized, allowing DNA polymerase to hook itself onto the DNA strand and perform replication. This process works well in organisms that have circular chromosomes, such as in prokaryotes, and in non chromosomal genetic information, like mitochondrial DNA. However, unlike these examples, eukaryotic organisms have a linear DNA strand. This creates a problem because the end of the strand, the space occupied by the primer (which is necessary to synthesize the new strand) is left not replicated. This results in successive loss and shortening at the end of the nascent DNA strand, which is lethal because cells with incorrect genomes are ultimately degraded. To solve this issue of “chewing up” the end of the chromatin, eukaryotic cells have long tandem repeated sequences at the end of the linear strands. This region of repeated sequences is called the telomere, and it is crucial, because replication will “eat away” at the ends of the strand. The excess of repeated sequences ensures that no genes are consumed at the end of the strand as the strand shortens. An additional enzyme, telomerase, lengthens the ends of the chromatin, maintaining the repeated sequences that comprise the telomere. Usually, cells are eventually marked for apoptosis, and the telomerase will no longer function in maintaining the repetitive sequences at the ends of the chromosome, and the “chewed up” DNA ultimately be degraded at the appropriate time.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Because of the relatively simple nature of the Drosophila chromosome, research has been able to observe and manipulate different aspects of the chromosome and identify gene locations. Polytene chromosomes are one specialized form of genetic information in eukaryotic organisms that have allowed researchers to identify gene locations. Polytene chromosomes are found in various cells in various organisms, but are not the normal form of genetic information. Polytene chromosomes are huge chromosomes that exist as paired homologs present in somatic cells. These chromosomes are the result of extensive DNA replication. Because they contain so many copies of identical genetic information, these excessive duplications appear as bands on the chromosomes. Each distinct band represents more than just one functional gene, and as such, it is still uncertain just how many genes are contained in each particular band. However, polytene chromosomes were nonetheless instrumental in the identification of many gene locations along the chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Unlike prokaryotic organisms that have simple circular chromosomes that are made entirely of essential genes, eukaryotic chromosomes have an extra layer of gene regulation accomplished by structural modifications to the linear DNA strands. Heterochromatic regions of the chromosome are areas in which structural modifications have effectively silenced, or disabled, the genetic information in this region from being accessible for transcription. These heterochromatic regions are dense, packed structures that consist of nucleosomes. The reason these regions stain dark is because they represent densely packed regions of genetic information, and they collectively absorb more stain. Nucleosomes are structures that arise along the strand of DNA that are comprised of eight histone proteins, each of which are wrapped 1.7 times with the strand of DNA. By wrapping DNA strands around these histone proteins, and then clumping theses wrapped bunches into even higher level structures of condensation, eukaryotic organisms can fit their massive linear DNA strand in the nucleus of every cell. However, there is a trade off in the condensed packing because the genes contained in the packed regions of the strand are silenced when they are in this form. On the other hand, euchromatic regions of the strand are the regions where the genes are accessible and therefore are active. These portions are linear, with plenty of space for the necessary enzymes and proteins involved in transcription to access the DNA sequence. These regions stain lighter because they much less dense regions of DNA, and the stain is less absorbed.
phenomenonA Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonA[comment] Epigenetic regulation of turning genes “off” and “on” impacts the genome in a variety of ways, including both chemical modifications (such as acetylation, methylation, and phosphorylation) as well as structural changes to the chromatin. These structural changes can lead to regions of genome becoming accessible or inaccessible for transcription, affecting gene expression. While these structural changes may not be via the same mechanism as what we traditionally associate with heterochromatic regions (nucleosome structures with eight histone proteins wrapped with DNA), the effects seen by both these OFF/ON mechanisms are similar in that they both represent the gene regulation that results from differential gene expression in various cells.
phenomenonB Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonB[comment] Malignant cells have been identified as having a mutation in the regulation of telomerase, the enzyme responsible for telomere formation and maintenance during the life cycle of a cell. In cancer cells, there has been research implicating the role of telomerase in aiding the cancer cells immortality. By continuing to maintain telomerase activity in a cell past the normal timing for apoptosis, these immortal cells are able to rapidly and exponentially divide far longer than normal cells. In addition to uncontrolled replication, more and more mutations accumulate in the DNA of these cancer cells (since they’re alive way longer than they should be). I think this concept was particularly interesting because cancer research is such a large and important aspect of current research in genetics.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that because of the linear chromosomes present in eukaryotic cells, the standard mechanism of DNA synthesis and replication result in a shortening of each successive nascent DNA strand. Obviously, this loss of genetic information could not be withstood in an organism. Without telomerase activity at the end of the chromosome maintaining the length of the telomeres, our chromosomes would be successively shortened until they were just degraded all together as nonfunctional. One aspect of this topic I am somewhat unsure about is the role of the telomere caps. I know that diseases can be associated with issues with the telomere cap itself or the telomerase enzyme itself. I don’t know how strongly I would be able to expand on this aspect of the role of telomeres in eukaryotic organisms.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that specialized chromosomes, called polytene chromosomes, were crucial in identifying gene locations on the chromosomes. While I can explain the features of polytene chromosomes, such as they are paired homologs in somatic cells that are massive and consist of a large number of identical DNA, I don’t fully understand how this is possible. It seems that the entirely of polytene chromosomes is not yet fully understood, since researchers are still unable to identify and quantify all of the specific genes in each of the bands. I understand the implications of polytene chromosomes, but I don’t have a firm grasp on their origin or how they can be created in the laboratory.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that differential staining of heterochromatic and euchromatic regions of the chromosome reflect the relative density of genetic material housed in each of these locations. I understand that heterochromatic regions are regions that have multiple stages and layers of chromatin condensation mechanisms in place to compact these regions. I also understand that these regions are dynamic, and that gene regulation and epigenetic factors can induced the conversion of various regions between these two conformational forms. I understand that the genes that are compacted in heterochromatic structures are not accessible for transcription, meaning they are effectively turned “off”, while euchromatic regions are accessible for transcription (all the various proteins and transcription factors associated with this process requires physical space around the chromosome). The only aspect of this topic I don’t feel totally comfortable with is how the epigenetic mechanisms of chemical modifications and structural changes interacts with this mechanism of gene regulation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that the process of DNA replication in eukaryotes and prokaryotes may appear similar at first glance, but in actually, the process is much different in pivotal ways. First, prokaryotic DNA replication involves the replication of a circular chromosome, while eukaryotic DNA replication involves the replication of a linear chromosome. As mentioned earlier, if DNA replication of the linear chromosome occurred in the same fashion as it does in circular DNA, the genetic material of eukaryotic organisms would be successively shorten with each round of replication (which would lead to unviable daughter cells). A second difference is that eukaryotic organisms use two different polymerases to copy the leading and lagging strand. A third difference is that DNA replication of the eukaryotic chromosome is much slower than in prokaryotic cells (25 times slower). The slow nature of DNA replication is made up for in eukaryotes by their fourth distinction, that is, having multiple origins of replication, versus prokaryotes that only have one origin of replication. The last main difference between DNA replication in eukaryotes and prokaryotes is the initiation of replication. In eukaryotes, primer RNA is replaced with DNA, and the origin of replication C protein (ORC) recognizes A-T rich regions and binds to the adjacent site.

groupTime450 40.4

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] DNA polymerase can only synthesize a new strand of DNA as it moves along the template strand in the 3' to 5' direction. This works fine for the 3' to 5' strand of the chromosome because the DNA polymerase can move uninterruptedly from the origin of replication until it meets another point of replication or the end of the chromosome. However this is only the case for 3' to 5'. Synthesis involving the 5' to 3' strand is discontinuous. Discontinuous replication produces a series of short DNA fragments called Okazaki fragments that are complementary to the template strand. These fragments are then covalently bound together by DNA ligase which forms a continuous chain of nucleotides which completes the replication of this strand.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Drosphilia showed us that there are polytene and lampbrush chromosomes. Drosphilia is an example of polytene. Polytene chromosomes are many-stranded chromosomes that have undergone numerous rounds of DNA replication without separation of the replicated strands which remain in exact parallel register. The result is a giant chromosome with aligned chromosomes displaying a characteristic banding pattern. Polytene are found in various tissues in the larvae of some flies as well as in several species of protozoans and plants. Polytene chromosomes can be seen in the nuclei of interphase cells.
explainConcepts[SQ003] While we know that eukaryotic DNA consists of continual double-helical fiber along its entire length, we also know that the whole chromosomes is not structurally uniform from end to end. This was discovered in 1928. Euchromatin is chromatin or chromosomal regions that are lightly staining and relatively uncoiled during the interphase portion of the cell cycle. This region contains most of the structural genes. Heterochromatin is the heavily staining, late-replicating regions of chromosomes that are prematurely condensed in interphase. Heterochromatin areas are genetically inactive because they either lack genes or contain genes that are repressed.
phenomenonA Specialized Drosophila chromosomes allowed the identification of gene locations.
phenomenonA[comment] If you can determine and identify various gene locations, then this can be beneficial in identifying and isolating various disease and genetic disorders. If you can determine where in the gene the mutation or problem is occurring, then you are more likely to be able to prevent it from happening or help fix it when it does. This can also be beneficial when looking at carriers and genetic disorder possibilities before a couple has children.
phenomenonB Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonB[comment] The crucial factor the determines cancer cells from normal cells is the ability of cancer cells/tissue to grow indefinitely. Almost all cancers express telomerase. If there was something to prevent the expression of the gene for telomerase or prevent the action of the enzyme, then there might be a new way to fight against cancer.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Telomeres help preserve the integrity and stability of the chromosomes. They create inert chromosomes ends, protecting intact eukaryotic chromosomes. The problem that arises is that at the gaps left at the 5' ends of the newly synthesized DNA. These gaps cannot be filled by DNA polymerase because no free 3'-OH groups are available for the synthesis. With each round of replication, the shortening becomes more severe in each daughter cell which eventually extends beyond the telomere and potentially deleting gene-coding regions.
explainConcepts[SQ002] These specialized chromosomes are called polytene chromosomes and they are found in various tissues in the larvae of some flies like Drosophila and plants. The bands of the polytene chromosomes was initially interpreted as the visible manifestation of individual genes. The study of these bands during development in Drosophila revealed differential gene activity.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The terms euchromatin and heterochromatin are used to describe the parts of chromosomes that are uncoiled and those that remained condensed. Heterochromatic area are genetically inactive because they either lack genes or contain genes that are repressed.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] Gaps remain on newly synthesized DNA strands at each successive round of synthesis shortening the double-stranded ends of the chromosomes by the length of the RNA primer. With each round of replication, the shortening becomes more severe in each daughter cell, eventually extending beyond the telomere and potentially deleting gene-coding regions. The solution to this is a unique eukaryotic enzyme called telomerase.
phenomenonB Specialized Drosophila chromosomes allowed the identification of gene locations.
phenomenonB[comment] By studying Drosophila and other flies were we able to discover Polytene Chromosomes. Also by studying these chromosomes we were able to discover differential gene activity.

Because of this problem an eukaryotic enzyme called telomerase is the solution to this problem. This enzyme is able to add several more repeats of the six-nucleotide sequence to the 3' end of the G-rich strand.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Because of the study of bands in Drosophila and other flies we were able to reveal different gene activity. This special chromosome is called a polytene chromosome. A characteristic pattern of band formation that is equated with gene activation is observed as development proceeds.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that euchromatin and heterochromatin were used to describe the parts of chromosomes that are uncoiled and those that remained condensed. Heterochromatic areas are genetically inactive because they either lack genes or contain genes that are repressed. In some cases, some chromosomes are completely heterochromatic.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] There are differences in the replication of DNA in eukaryotes and prokaryotes. In prokaryotes DNA replication happens in the cytoplasm while in eukaryotes it happens in the nucleus. Prokaryotes only have one origin of replication per DNA molecule while eukaryotes have and origin of replication of many (over 1000). These are just a few of the differences between DNA replication of prokaryotes and eukaryotes, but there are many differences in how DNA replicate in each.

explainConcepts[SQ002] Drosophila chromosomes have "puffs" which are easily visible portions of their chromosomes where one can see areas of high gene activity. It allowed scientists to identify gene locations.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Euchromatin are uncoiled and contain many, active genes. These appear lightly stained during interphase whereas heterochromatin are condensed areas of chromatin with little gene activity that appear darkly stained during interphase. Little transcription takes place for the condensed chromatin because they are wrapped around the histones.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] Telomeres are extremely important in protecting the DNA from degradation even though they cause problems during transcription. Loss of telomeres is associated with aging. Telomerase must add RNA in order for DNA to be added through reverse transcription. Then DNA polymerase can attach and copy the DNA.
phenomenonB Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonB[comment] Euchromatic regions are those that have many, active genes. They are active because the DNA has been unwound from the histones so that it can be transcribed. The heterochromatic regions are those that either have few genes or are regions that have been deactivated. The DNA stays wound around the histones so it can't be transcribed.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] After each duplication, DNA is shorter at it's 5' end than the parental DNA strand. This causes an overhang at the 3' end of each daughter double helix. Telomeres are repetitive sequences that protect the important genes from being deleted. Once these telomeric regions are lost, the DNA risks losing sequences with further replication. This is being studied to somewhat inhibit the aging process.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Polytene chromosomes are oversized chromosomes which have developed from standard chromosomes. These chromosomes have characteristic dark and light bands that can be used to locate and identify rearrangements and deletions. The light bands correspond to locations of high transcriptional activity.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Introns are noncoding regions of the gene while exons are the parts of the gene that code for a final part of mature RNA. The introns are spliced out during transcription. Prokaryotes have relatively fewer introns than eukaryotes. These noncoding regions contain ancient human DNA as well as viral.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] The study of telomere shortening may lead to ways to lessen the effects of aging. As telomeres shorten the DNA has a higher change to lose a critical gene. If the shortening of telomeres could be accomplished, then organ function and essentially life would be prolonged.
phenomenonB Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonB[comment] It has recently become evident that introns may have played a critical role in our evolution. Based on conserved location of introns it is becoming increasingly clear that introns perform important functions such as regulating gene expression. One study has shown that early animal genomes were rich with introns and that a large fraction of the introns present within the human genome likely originated early in evolution followed by a high degree of intron loss later in evolution as these noncoding regions were rapidly lost in early eukaryotic cells.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Telomeres are regions of repetitive nucleotide sequences at the end of a chromosome. They protect the chromosome from deterioration. During gene replication, the whole chromosome is not replicated and it becomes truncated. The telomere protects the gene and acts as a buffer that gets cut off a little during replication. Telomeres deteriorate over time and telomerase reverse transcriptase is an enzyme that replenishes them.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Polytene chromosomes were first observed in the salivary glands of drosophila. Polytene chromosomes are specialized cells that undergo several rounds of DNA replication without cell division to form one large chromosome. Their purpose is to expand the cell and increase cell volume.
explainConcepts[SQ003] During interphase, you can see euchromatin and heterochromatin. Euchromatin are genes that are being actively transcribed and are less compacted (uncoiled) than the heterochromatin which remain coiled and are not undergoing transcription. Euchromatin contain active genes and heterochromatin contain few genes or repressed genes.
phenomenonA Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonA[comment] The heterochromatin are more dense and compacted than the euchromatin and will stain darker than the euchromatin.
phenomenonB Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonB[comment] Research is being done that looks at telomeres as the key to cancer. When a cell becomes cancerous, it divides rapidly and the telomeres become shorter. Researchers have blocked telomerase that would add more telomeres to the end of the cancerous chromosomes. When the telomeres run out, the cell ages and dies.

groupTime450 21.32

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Linear eukaryotic chromosomes end in distinctive sequences called telomeres, which help preserve the stability and integrity of the chromosomes. They create inert chromosome ends that protect the chromosomes from improper fusion or degradation. When eukaryotic cells undergo DNA replication, RNA primers provide the 3'-OH necessary to initiate synthesis. However, at the 5' ends of newly synthesized DNA, there are gaps that cannot be filled by DNA polymerase because there are no free 3'-OH groups for the initiation of synthesis. Thus, the replicated strands are shorter than the template strands since there are gaps at the end. Over time. this could be a problem as strands become shorter and shorter after each replication. However, telomerase serves to fix this problem by pairing part of an RNA strand with the end of the sequence of the single-stranded overhanging DNA while the rest extends beyond this overhang. Then reverse transcription produces an extension of the DNA strand. Then, once the telomere has been lengthened by this activity,conventional DNA synthesis ensues.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Both polytene chromosomes and lampbrush chromosomes are types of chromosomes discovered in Drosophila that have allowed identification of gene locations. Polytene chromosomes exhibit a linear series of alternating bands and interbands, producing a pattern that is distinctive for each chromosome in any given species. The presence of bands on the chromosome is actually the visible manifestation of individual genes. Bands revel differential gene activity and can help distinguish locations. Lampbrush chromosomes do not condense as normal meiotic chromosomes do but instead extend to great lengths. Lampbrush chromosomes have a pair of lateral loops emanating from each of them, and much more DNA is present in these loops than in the rest of the chromosomes. These loops represent DNA that has been reeled out from the central chromosome axis during transcription.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Euchromatin describe the parts of the chromosome that are uncoiled and thus able to be transcribed into mRNA to begin the process of producing proteins. Meanwhile, heterochromatin is condensed regions of the chromosomes that cannot be transcribed to produce mRNA and later proteins. This shows that not all of the DNA always encodes proteins.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] It is believed that as chromosomes that do not benefit from the activity of telomerase replicate over and over throughout and individual's lifetime, the chromosomes shorten with each replication until the cell loses the ability to replicate. Most stem cells, and malignant cells maintain telomerase activity and this may contribute to their immortality. Therefore, if a cancer cell does not experience telomere shortening it can replicate an infinite number of times.
phenomenonB Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonB[comment] The centromeres of chromosomes are believed to be composed of dense heterochromatic regions of chromosomes.

I understand that as this happens with each successive replication of a DNA strand, the strand further shortens until is eventually can no longer replicate. I understand that this can cause problems with health, but that the enzyme telomerase helps to prevent this.I understand that this enzyme binds to the overhanging DNA strand and extends an RNA strand from which an addition to the template DNA strand is produced through reverse transcription. I understand that then, replication can take place through conventional methods and produce a normal length DNA strand.

Also, because eukaryotic chromosomes are linear they have a problem caused by telomere shortening while prokaryotic chromosomes that are circular are not subject to this problem.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] In order for 5' to 3' replication to occur, the template has to be discontinuous.Gaps will remain on newly synthesized DNA strands, which shortens the double-stranded ends of the chromosome by the length of the RNA primer. Each round of replication, the shortening becomes more severe in each daughter cell.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that telomeres are repetitive sequences that code for no particular gene. These telomeres protect the important genes from being deleted as cells divide and as DNA strands shorten during replication. After each round of DNA replication, some telomeric sequences are lost at the 5' end of the newly synthesized strand on each daughter DNA, but because theres are noncoding sequences, their loss does not adversely affect the cell. Telomeres prevent the shortening and loss of information on the daughter DNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that polytene chromosomes have characteristic light and dark banding patterns that can be used to identify chromosomal rearrangements and deletions. Dark banding frequently corresponds to inactive chromatin that isn't being transcribed and light banding frequently corresponds to active chromatin that is being transcribed. The banding patterns of the chromosomes of the polytene chromosomes are especially helpful in research as they provide an excellent visualization of transcriptionally active chromatin and the general chromatin structure in general. Chromosome puffs are diffused uncoiled regions of the polytene chromosome that are sites of RNA transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that chromatin is in the nucleus and is packaged by proteins called histones. There are two types of chromatin. Euchromatin is a lightly packaged form of DNA, lightly stained, and actively transcribed. Heterochromatin is tightly packed form of DNA, dark stained, and not actively transcribed. This differential packaging is used as a mechanism of gene regulation, with stable silencing of large domains achieved by packaging the DNA in a certain way.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that DNA replication in eukaryotes and prokaryotes differ. DNA replication in prokaryotes occurs inside the cytoplasm and DNA replication in eukaryotes occurs inside the nucleus. In prokaryotes, there is only one origin of replication per DNA molecule, origin of replication is formed of about 100-200 or more nucleotides, replication of DNA occurs at one point in each prokaryotic molecule, only two replication fork is formed during each replicating prokaryotic chromosome, has one replicon, and one replication bubble is formed during DNA replication. In eukaryotes, origin of replication are many (over 1000) in each eukaryotic chromosome, each origin of replication is formed of about 150 nucleotides, replication of DNA occurs at several points simultaneously in each chromosome, a number of replication forks are formed simultaneously, large number of replicons, and numerous relocation bubbles are formed in one replicating DNA molecule.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Linear chromosomes are capped with sequences of DNA called telomeres that help prevent degradation of important genetic material. Because DNA polymerase cannot add nucleotides to the ends of linear chromosomes, the 5' end is left shorter than the 3' causing problems in eukaryotic DNA replication. An enzyme telomerase helps alleviate this problem by adding DNA sequences to the end of eukaryotic chromosomes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Polytene chromosomes found in the Drosophila are specialized, over-sized chromososomes that are formed from multiple rounds of DNA replication. The resulting sister chromatids remain synapsed. These chromosomes allow an increased level of gene expression. These chromosomes consist of light and dark banding patterns that can be used to identify chromosomal deletions and rearrangements. The dark banding generally correlates with silent non-transcripitionally active DNA whereas the light banding DNA generally correlates with transcriptionally active genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Chromosomes are composed of two different types chromatin, euchromatin and heterochromatin. Euchromatin stains light and typically corresponds to areas of high transcriptional activity. Heterochromatin stains dark and typically corresponds to areas of low transcriptional activity. Depending on where a gene lies (in euchromatin or heterochromatin) its level of gene expression varies.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] Without addition cellular process involving enzymes such as telomerase, which synthesizes telomeres, linear chromosomes would be shortened and degraded after each round of replication. This could cause devastating loses of genetic material.
phenomenonB Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonB[comment] Depending on a genes location within a chromosome it's level of transcriptional active will differ. If found in a euchromatic, or transcriptionaly active, region the gene will be transcriptionaly active than those found in heterochromatic, or silent regions.

explainConcepts[SQ001] After DNA replication, linear chromosomes have a problem. This is because after replication, the newly synthesized DNA strand is shorter at the five prime end than the parent strand. Therefore, there is a three prime overhang at one end of the daughter strand. Therefore, opposite ends have this three prime overhang. DNA polymerase cannot replace the RNA with DNA, therefore, eventually, the entirety of the DNA would be lost. Therefore, linear chromosomes have telomeres.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Polytene chromosomes are in many tissues of the Drosophila fly, including salivary, rectal, midgut, excretory tubules of the fly. The puffs in these chromosomes represent gene activity. These bulges or puffs show were there is a lot of gene activity or where the transcription produces RNA.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Heterochromatin can be either constitutive or facultative. Constitutive heterochromatin affects the genes around it and can form telomeres or centromeres. It also can be used for gene expression or repression signals. Facultative heterochromatin is generally the result of silenced genes, however it can become active by losing its condensed structure. Euchromatin generally contains the most active portion of the genome. It is usually under active transcription.

explainConcepts[SQ001] When chromosomes are replicated, the telomere is the end of linear chromosomes that keep genes from getting deleted as replication occurs. explainConcepts[SQ002] Polytene chromosomes are specialized, over sized chromosomes that result from repeated DNA replication without cell division resulting a giant clump of DNA. What makes these useful is that the have light and dark banded areas with light areas corresponding to high replication areas while the dark spots indicate inactive chromatin. Using these light and dark bands show areas that transcription occurs at most often and allowed scientists to follow all genes that are replicated to show that each cell contains the same genes.

groupTime450 41.5

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Telomeres, the G rich series at the end of chromosomes, present a problem on the lagging strand. When the RNA primer is removed there is not a free 3’ OH group for DNA polymerase I to fill in the gaps. Thus the lagging strand is shorter than the leading strand. If this segment is not lengthened, it will shorten with each replication and can eventually affect the regions of the chromosomes that encode genes. This problem is resolved via Telomerase and enzyme with an RNA segment that pairs with the overhang on the leading strand and extends the lagging strand so that the chromosome is not shorter.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Polytene and lampbrush chromosomes are unusual and not typically found in most cells but the study of their structure has allowed for identifying gene locations. The study of the many bands in polytene chromosomes shows gene activity. While we do not know how many genes are encoded in each band, it is known that each band contains much more DNA than is needed active genes. Polytene chromosomes are paired homologs which is highly unusual. They have extensive banding and form “puffs” which represent areas of gene activity. Lampbrush chromosomes are very large with extensive DNA looping and are easily isolated during prophase I of meiosis. The loops in lampbrush chromosomes are similar to polytene chromosomes puffs as they represent sites of gene activity
explainConcepts[SQ003] Chromosomes are composed of two regions: euchromatin and heterochromatin. The areas of light staining (euchromatin) contain active genes that are being expressed, while in heterochromatin there are no active genes present. The differences in staining allow researchers to identify areas where genes are active.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] Telomeres and telomerase activity are extremely important in aging. If telomerase is not present to cap the ends of chromosomes, the individual’s chromosomes will shorten with each successive replication and the individual will age sharply.
phenomenonB Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonB[comment] This is extremely important in identifying active genes and areas where genes are not being expressed. This can also be used in mapping genes and as it allows researchers to determine heterochromatic areas where genes are not expressed.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Linear chromosomes cause a problem when both the leading strand and the lagging strand are being replicated at the very end of the chromosome. This is because the RNA primer leaves a gap at the end of the replicating strands that DNA polymerase cannot fill. The deletion eventually extends beyond the telomere and deletes gene coding regions.
explainConcepts[SQ002] There are two specialized drosophila chromosomes, the polytene chromosome, and the lampbrush chromosome. The polytene chromosome stands out in that puffs are created from a high level of gene activity at certain areas along the chromosome. The lampbrush chromosome is similar to the polytene chromosome, in that they are both sites of increased gene activity.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Chromosomes have areas where transcription is actively taking place during interphase, theses areas stain lightly because the chromosome is uncoiled at this location and are known as euchromatin. On the other hand, areas that stain darkly are known as heterochramatin, and are condensed areas where transcription is not taking place.
phenomenonA Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonA[comment] Heterochromatin is unique to eukaryotes. Barr bodies are a perfect example of an entire heterochromatic chromosome. This is why poly x does not affect the female any differently than the normal XX female.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Telomeres are repeating sequences at the end of chromosomes that protect the chromosome from being shortened. Telomeres prevent this by acting as a buffer to shortening of the chromosome, so the non-coding telomeres are degraded instead. Telomeres are lengthened by telomerase, and telomeres are always shortened on the lagging strand. The lengthening of telomeres by drugs and gene therapy has been postulated as a possible solution for aging; however, telomere lengthening has also shown a high correlation with cancer cells.
explainConcepts[SQ002] These specialized Drosophila chromosomes are called polytene chromosomes. Polytene chromosomes start out as normal chromosomes but are replicated many times with no cell division. This causes the chromosomes to have many copies that are paired together, allowing scientists to see intricate banding patterns across the chromosomes. This allows researchers to see the specific locations of genes on the chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Euchromatic regions of chromosomes are regions that are read by RNA polymerase, so these regions code for genes. Heterochromatin (usually close to the centromere in a chromosome but also elsewhere) is usually non-coding because it is so tightly wound up. This is also why the heterochromatin stains darker compared to euchromatin—it is denser. Because it is more tightly coiled, it is not read by RNA polymerase. Many times the tight coiling is caused by methylation.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] This phenomenon is evident in many scientific disciplines, such as geriatrics or oncology.
phenomenonB Specialized Drosophila chromosomes allowed the identification of gene locations.
phenomenonB[comment] Seeing the polytene chromosomes in Drosophila has allowed us to determine specific gene locations in flies, so we are able to do much better research on various topics when we use fruit flies.

groupTime450 24.98

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] While prokaryotes have circular DNA that does not reach a fatal end point, eukaryotes have linear DNA that must end. These ends risk degradation and therefore ruining of crucial genes. This problem can be assuaged with telomeres. Telomeres add additional non-coding genes with the help of the protein telomerase. With time, telomeres will shorten and induce aging. However, telomeres do not shorten in cancer cells. This produces a problem in that telomeres aid in propagating the life span of harmful cancer cells.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Chromosomes can and must be packaged in a variety of intricate, specialized ways in order to fit into nuclei that are much smaller than their fully extended length. Drosophila chromosomes are packaged in a special way in which strands of chromosomes are lined up next to their same genes, creating lines indicating areas of certain same genes. This arrangement is referred to as a polytene chromosome and helps identify gene locations since the genes are much more visible in larger amounts.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Post-transcriptional regulation affects gene expression by manipulating nucleosome packaging. Acetylation causes the nucleosome to "unwind," allowing the DNA and associated histone proteins to relax and stretch out, enabling the DNA to be read by DNA polymerase; methylation induces the opposite effect, causing the nucleosome to reassemble. When a nucleosome is unwound and the DNA can be read, active transcription is occurring and the chromosome stains lightly, indicating it is euchromatic. When a nucleosome is tightly packed and the DNA cannot be read, the histone-DNA clumps stain darkly, indicating it is heterochromatic.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] Extending the life of telomeres could be the key to longer lives, and some claim it to be the "key to immortality."
phenomenonB Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonB[comment] The different colors visible in staining regions of chromosomes can be used for DNA identification purposes, as in for forensic cases.

I understand that telomeres add additional non-coding genes. I understand that over time, telomeres shorten and induce senescence as a result of repeated cell division. I also understand, however, that in cancer cells, telomeres do not shorten. The lack of telomere shortening in cancer cells produces a problem in that telomeres aid in propagating the life span of the deadly condition.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that because the extended lengths of chromosomes are much longer than would fit in their nuclei, chromosomes undergo specialized, intricate packaging. I understand that as a result of this downsizing necessity and the failure of certain genes to divide after replication, Drosophila chromosomes ma be arranged in a special way: the chromosome strands are lined up adjacent to their same genes, creating lines indicating areas of certain same genes. I understand that this arrangement (polytene chromosomes) enables genes to be identified more clearly since they are present in bulk.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that gene expression can be affected after transcription with the manipulation of nucleosome packaging. I understand that histone acetylation causes the nucleosome to "unwind" and enables the DNA to be read by DNA polymerase; methylation induces the opposite effect, causing the nucleosome to reassemble and hindering it from being reached by DNA polymerase. I understand that an unwound, readable nucleosome undergoes active transcription and stains lightly, indicating it is euchromatic. Likewise, I understand that a tightly packed, non-readable nucleosome has essentially no transcription and stains darkly, indicating it is heterochromatic.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that while they share some major similarities, the intricacies of replication in prokaryotes and eukaryotes have numerous differences. There is only one point of origin in prokaryotes, and replication and occurs in two opposite directions at the same time; in eukaryotes, there are multiple points of origin, and replication is unidirectional. Replication in prokaryotes takes place in the cytoplasm; in eukaryotes, it takes place in the nucleus. Two types of polymerase are used by prokaryotic cells; eukaryotes utilize four or more different types. Prokaryotic replication occurs at a slower rate than eukaryotic replication. While prokaryotes have continuous chromosomes, eukaryotes utilize telomeres to extend their finite, linear chromosomes. Prokaryote replication occurs much more often since eukaryotic only occurs during S phase.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] I do not know much information about telomere replication, but I do know that the amount of telomeres have been associated with cancer and youth, but on the opposite ends of the spectrum. Furthermore, shortened telomeres have been noticed and associated with cancer cells but longer telomere sequences have been associated with aging, thus making it a prime candidate for research especially during DNA replication. Telomeres are tandem repeats found at the end of chromosomes that are produced by the enzyme called telomerase so the actual genes on a chromosome do not get affected by cell replication and cell division during mitosis in somatic cells. The enzyme telomerase controls the amount of sequenced telomeres are placed and paired since DNA polymerase cannot add bases to the ends of linear chromosomes due to a problem from RNA primers. I unfortunately do not know the problem that was caused, but would like to know more information about this issue.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Two specialized chromosomes that brought more knowledge about the basic structure of a chromosome -specifically chromatin- were Polytene and Lampbrush chromosomes. Lampbrush chromosomes were commonly found in amphibians; whereas, Polytene chromosomes were known to be specialized chromosomes found in Drosophila. Polytene chromosomes were found to be replicated innumerable times, but fail to undergo cell division which results in the large size of the Polytene chromosomes. Furthermore, since the staining patterns indicated that these specialized forms of chromosomes are highly composed of euchromatin, the multiple copies allow an increase in protein production through gene expression of the multiple genes. These Polytene chromosomes enabled researchers to determine certain banding patterns within the Polytene chromosomes as well allowed a structure of chromatin in Eukayotes to be noticed and constructed. These banding patterns provided further confirmation to two notions. The first being that all the cells within an organism contain the same genome or carry the entire set of chromosomes, but gene expression and regulation allows for cell differentiation. The second important thing enabled by specific banding patterns was the ability to notice certain gene mutations with ease such as translocations and frame-shift mutations.
explainConcepts[SQ003] When staining chromosomes, two methods-- C banding and G banding, can be used. These banding techniques produce banding patterns that are unique for each chromosome. G-banding, in my opinion, is more useful than C-banding in the sense that more information can be told from the band patterns in G-banding especially in the scenario of a genetic disease. These banding patterns are dependent upon if the gene is highly transcribed or rarely transcribed; the genes that are highly transcribed are known as euchromatin since the gene is able to produce an actual element (amino acid), whereas, those genes that are never transcribed are heterochromatin and cannot produce an amino acid in regular circumstances. The centromeres of chromosomes are shown to be highly composed of heterochromatin since the centromere region is stained darkly with the Giemsa stain which is indicated in C-banding.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] DNA replication within Eukaryotes is much more complex than DNA replication in prokaryotes from the number of enzymes and proteins that play a role within DNA replication and the process of replication itself. For instance in Eukaryotes, an enzyme called Helicase unzips the DNA strand into its two components which will later be called the leading strand (5' to 3' direction) and the lagging strand (3' to 5' direction). The leading strand has continuous synthesis of the DNA complementary base pairs which is accomplished by various DNA polymerase and an RNA primer; whereas the lagging strand is discontinuous. This discontinuous synthesis produces Okazaki Fragments which require multiple RNA primers and DNA polymerases to attach complementary base pairs in fractions leaving spaces in between the complementary bases which is sealed by another enzyme called ligase. In prokaryotes, however, a replication fork is formed at the point of origin and single-stranded binding proteins (SSBP) like that in Eukaryotes keeps the DNA held separated instead of rejoining immediately after the un-fastening of the DNA strand. While the prokaryotic Helicase is unwinding or unraveling the DNA, a portion becomes supercoiled. Furthermore, DNA replication in prokaryotes is also bi-directional as well; however, a major difference between prokaryotes and eukaryotes is the number of origin of initiation or ORI. Prokaryotes have only one while eukaryotes can have multiple ORI which creates an ease at replicating DNA since Eukaryotes have much more DNA than Prokaryotes.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Telomeres of chromosomes shorten with each cell division. In most eukaryotic somatic cells, telomerase is not active. Stem cells and malignant cells maintain telomerase activity which immortalizes them. Telomerase activity and telomere length linked to aging, cancer, and other diseases.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Specialized Chromosomes revealed variations in the organization of DNA. Polytene chromosomes represent paired homologs. THey are unusual and are usually not found in eukaryotic cells. They can be visualized by light microscopy and can be seen in nuclei of interphase cells. These chromosomes are found in various tissues: salivary, rectal, midgut, and excretory tubules of Drosophila.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Euchromatin and Heterochromatin are areas of chromosomes. Euchromatin is uncoiled and active. It appears unstained during interphase. Heterochromatin are condensed areas are mostly inactive. It appears stained during interphase.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] In prokaryotic cells, there is only one point of origin, replication occurs in two opposing directions at the same time, and takes place in the cell cytoplasm. Eukaryotic cells on the other hand, have multiple points of origin, and use unidirectional replication within the nucleus of the cell. Prokaryotic cells possess one or two types of polymerases, whereas eukaryotes have four or more.

groupTime450 46.15

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A problem is created in linear chromosomes because after replication the 5' end is shorter than the parental 5' end. This leads to the 3' end to overhang. This leads to the RNA primer of the 5' end not being replaced with DNA, so the daughter cells have incomplete strands of DNA. These overhanging strands are digested by nucleases, which over time leads to the strand becoming shorter and shorter. This is why telomeres exist on DNA strands, in order to protect the important genes from being degraded over time.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Drosophila have specialized chromosomes called polytene chromosomes which allow the identification of gene locations. These chromosomes are paired homologs and are unusual. They are found in the salivary, rectal, midgut, and excretory tubules of the Drosophila. Puffs in the the chromosome represent areas of gene activity and location of that gene. Bulges show DNA which has uncoiled and are signs of high gene activity.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Euchromatic chromosomes are euchromatin, while heterochromatic chromosomes are heterochromatin. Euchromatin is uncoiled, active, and is unstained during interphase. Heterochromatin is stained and appears condensed in inactive regions. Heterochromatin usually contain far fewer genes that euchromatin and are also much more compact than euchromatin.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] The essential problem with linear chromosomes is that they tend to shorten over time as replication occurs over and over. This is due to the 5' end being shorter on the daughter strand and the 3' end hanging over. The excess DNA strand becomes digested, thus shortening the DNA. Telomeres protect the ends of the DNA by providing random copies of bases to protect essential coding DNA from being degraded. A biological phenomenon linked to this is aging. If the shortening of DNA can be reversed or stopped, then aging can be curbed to be much slower than it is.
phenomenonB Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonB[comment] Euchromatin and heterochromatin refer to light and dark stained chromatin. One is active while the other is not actively transcribing. A biological phenomenon related to this is gene expression. These regions can pinpoint what genes are going to be expressed and which ones are not. This is extremely useful to see whether a person will exhibit a specific trait or not.

The 3' end overhangs, so the DNA strand is digested by nucleases to make it a complete strand. However, over time this leads to shorter strands of DNA. Eventually, this strand of DNA disappears. These ends are protected by telomeres which protect essential DNA fragments from being degraded.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand this concept because I know that the specialized chromosomes in Drosophila are the polytene chromosomes which allow the identification of gene locations. Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] DNA polymerase cannot replicate and repair DNA molecules at the ends of linear chromosomes. The ends of linear chromosome have telomeres, which protect genes from getting deleted as cells divide. The telomerase enzyme attaches to the end of the chromosome, and complementary RNA bases are added on the 3' end of the DNA. Once the lagging strand is elongated by telomerase, DNA polymerase can add to the ends of the chromosomes and the telomeres are replicated. This 5' to 3' replication is seen in eukaryotes because DNA cannot be replicated 3' to 5' so the cell must have mechanisms to make up for this.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The banding patterns of Drosophila chromosomes were sketched in 1935 by Calvin B. Bridges. This was done in such detail that these maps are still used. The banding patterns of the chromosomes are helpful in research because they provide a visualization of transcriptionally active chromatin as well as the general chromatin structure. The Drosophila chromosomes have been used to support the theory of genomic equivalence, which states that all of the cells in the body maintain the same genome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Chromosomes have characteristic light banding and dark banding patterns. The dark banding usually corresponds to inactive chromatin, and the light banding is usually found at areas with higher transcriptional activity, meaning these segments are active. These banding patterns can be used to identify chromosomal rearrangements and deletions.
phenomenonA Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonA[comment] I have actually seen DNA banding techniques performed in a lab. We were able to take DNA and run specific techniques to see which areas of the DNA were active and which were not. The active regions corresponded to the light banding patterns.
phenomenonB Specialized Drosophila chromosomes allowed the identification of gene locations.
phenomenonB[comment] I think this project was very important and useful because it helped us understand DNA and the DNA genome in greater detail. This experiment helped to lay the platform for the work on the human genome. It also help create techniques to view chromosomes and identify them.
