Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] After replication of DNA, RNA primers are removed, creating gaps. The gaps have free OH groups that initiate the synthesis of new DNA by polymerase and then they are sealed by ligaase. The gaps at the left end of the 5' do not have free OH groups. With each replication, the daughter DNA strand become shorter. This is fixed by the enzyme telemerase. Replication of DNA using RNA occurs and is called reverse transcriptase.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Specialized chromosomes in the drosophila that helped identify specific gene locations are called polytene chromosomes. Polytene chromosomes are specific types of interphase chromosomes consisting of thousands of DNA strands. The chromosomes have a distinctive band pattern along the axis of the chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The DNA in the nucleus exists in two forms that reflect the level of activity of the cell. Heterochromatin appears as small, darkly staining parts scattered throughout the nucleus or accumulated adjacent to the nuclear envelope. Euchromatin is dispersed and not readily stainable. Euchromatin is prevalent in cells that are active in the transcription of many of their genes while heterochromatin is most abundant in cells that are less active or not active. There are more euchromatic parts of the chromosome than heterochromatic. The presence of heterochromatin is characteristic of eukaryotes.
phenomenonA Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonA[comment] An example of euchromatin is housekeeping cells. They are always turned on because they code for the proteins that are needed for basic cell survival.
phenomenonB Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonB[comment] Even though heterochromatin is usually inactive, it contributes greatly to biological function of DNA. It helps in the chromosome segregation during cell division.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The problem with linear chromosomes is that the ends of the chromosomes resembles that double stranded breaks that can occur in DNA which can lead to fusion and translocation. The solution to this is telomeres which are long sequences at the end of the DNA strand. A problem with telomeres is that they become shorter after replication and the shortening becomes more severe with each generation. The solution to this is the enzyme telomerase. Telomerase is able to lengthen the telomeres which essentially eliminates the shortening of the telomeres.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The two types of specialized chromosomes discussed in the text are polytene chromosomes and lampbrush chromosomes. I didn't remember this from lecture so upon reading the text I have learned that the polytene chromosomes are giant chromosomes that appear in a pattern of bands and interbands. Study of these bands in Drosophila showed a characteristic pattern that is linked to gene activation. Lampbrush chromosomes are chromosomes that actually lengthen instead of condensing before returning to their normal length during meiosis. The chromosomes exhibit loops whose shape represents DNA that has been reeled out from a central chromomere axis during transcription.
explainConcepts[SQ003] While euchromatin uncoil during interphase to become active and therefore stain light, heterochromatin stay condensed which causes them to stain deeply. The inactivity in heterochromatic areas is caused by genes being repressed or even not present. Telomeres are a type of heterochromatic region of the chromosome. They aren't active but they are important to the maintenance of the structural integrity of the chromosome.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonA[comment] The problems with linear chromosomes can cause translocations according to the text and translocations are the source of many genetic disorders that we have previously studied in class and the genetic disorders have been the most interesting biological phenomenon we've looked at this semester to me.

phenomenonB[comment] The specialized chromosomes in Drosophila, lampbrush chromosomes and polytene chromosomes, have been useful for the location of genes which could provide insight into what genes are responsible for certain traits in humans which is a biological phenomenon that I find particularly interesting.

groupTime451 757.8

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] ThTelomoeres,the ends of linear chromosomes, protect genes from getting deleted as cells continue to divide. This helps keep unwanted and problematic substances and genes from attaching to the chromosome where they shouldn't. The telomerase enzyme attaches to the end of the chromosome; complementary bases to the RNA template are added on the 3' end of the DNA strand. As DNA polymerase alone cannot replicate the ends of chromosomes, telomerase aids in their replication and prevents chromosome degradation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Specialized Drosophila chromosomes allowed the identification of gene locations. They were able to mark and track the genes on the chromosomes. This allowed scientists to plot and identify the locations of the genes marked on the chromosomes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The eukaryote's nucleus contains two types of chromatin: euchromatin, which is relatively loosely condensed and transcriptionally active, and heterochromatin, which is more tightly condensed and transcriptionally inactive. Heterochromatin also tends to replicate later in S phase than does euchromatin. In condensed chromosomes, we typically see heterochromatin around the centromere. Often about a third of a condensed chromosome is pericentric heterochromatin. There is also usually telomeric heterochromatin
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] DNA replication occurs within a cell in preparation for cell division to try to make sure that the new cells that are formed have the exact copy of genetic material from the parent cell. The differences between prokaryotic and eukaryotic DNA replication are largely related to contrasts in size and complexity of the DNA and cells of these organisms. The average eukaryotic cell has 25 times more DNA than a prokaryotic cell. In prokaryotic cells, there is only one point of origin, replication occurs in two opposing directions at the same time, and takes place in the cell cytoplasm. Eukaryotic cells on the other hand, have multiple points of origin, and use unidirectional replication within the nucleus of the cell.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Every RNA primer synthesized during replication can be removed and replaced with DNA strands except the RNA primer at the 5' end of the newly synthesized strand. This small section of RNA can only be removed, not replaced with DNA. Enzymes RNase H and FEN1 remove RNA primers, but DNA Polymerase will add new DNA only if the DNA Polymerase has an existing strand 5' to it ("behind" it) to extend. However, there is no more DNA in the 5' direction after the final RNA primer, so DNA polymerase cannot replace the RNA with DNA. Therefore, both daughter DNA strands have an incomplete 5' strand with 3' overhang
explainConcepts[SQ002] Polytene chromosomes are over-sized chromosomes which have developed from standard chromosomes and are commonly found in the salivary glands of Drosophila melanogaster. Specialized cells undergo repeated rounds of DNA replication withoutcell division (endomitosis), to increase cell volume, forming a giant polytene chromosome. Polytene chromosomes form when multiple rounds of replication produce many sister chromatids that remain synapsed together.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Heterochromatin is a tightly packed form of DNA, which comes in multiple varieties. These varieties lie on a continuum between the two extremes of constitutive and facultative heterochromatin. Both play a role in the expression of genes. Constitutive heterochromatin can affect the genes near them (position-effect variegation). It is usually repetitive and forms structural functions such as centromeres or telomeres, in addition to acting as an attractor for other gene-expression or repression signals. Facultative heterochromatin is the result of genes that are silenced through a mechanism such as histone deacetylation or piRNA through RNAi.
phenomenonA Chromosomes are composed of euchromatic (light staining regions of active transcription) and heterochromatic (dark staining regions with essentially no transcription).
phenomenonA[comment] They use this phenomenon in epigenetic twin study to examine the differences in the epigenome between to i identical twins
phenomenonB Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes
phenomenonB[comment] every time a cell replicates telomeres shorten and this has been shown to have an aging affect on the cell

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Linear chromosomes have an end problem. After DNA replication, each newly synthesized DNA strand is shorter at its 5' end than at the parental DNA strand's 5' end. This produces a 3' overhang at one end (and one end only) of each daughter DNA strand, such that the two daughter DNAs have their 3' overhangs at opposite ends
explainConcepts[SQ002] They are able to find where the gene activity is taking place on the chromosome for specific genes using polytene chromosomes
explainConcepts[SQ003] The lightly packed material is called euchromatin. Though it is lightly packed in the form of DNA, RNA, and protein, it is definitely rich in gene concentration and is usually under active transcription.On the other hand, heterochromatin is a tightly packed form of DNA. It is commonly found on the peripheral areas of the nucleus.
phenomenonA Linear chromosomes with telomeres create a problem with 5’ to 3’ replication in Eukaryotes

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Linear chromosomes have an end problem. After DNA replication, each newly synthesized DNA strand is shorter at its 5' end than at the parental DNA strand's 5' end. This produces a 3' overhang at one end (and one end only) of each daughter DNA strand, such that the two daughter DNAs have their 3' overhangs at opposite ends
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] They are able to find where the gene activity is taking place on the chromosome for specific genes using polytene chromosomes
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The lightly packed material is called euchromatin. Though it is lightly packed in the form of DNA, RNA, and protein, it is definitely rich in gene concentration and is usually under active transcription.On the other hand, heterochromatin is a tightly packed form of DNA. It is commonly found on the peripheral areas of the nucleus.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] In prokaryotic cells, there is only one point of origin, replication occurs in two opposing directions at the same time, and takes place in the cell cytoplasm. Eukaryotic cells on the other hand, have multiple points of origin, and use unidirectional replication within the nucleus of the cell. Prokaryotic cells possess one or two types of polymerases, whereas eukaryotes have four or more. Replication also happens at a much faster rate in prokaryotic cells.In addition, eukaryotes also have a distinct process for replicating the telomeres at the ends of their chromosomes. With their circular chromosomes, prokaryotes have no ends to synthesize. Lastly, the short replication in prokaryotes occurs almost continuously, but eukaryotic cells only undergo DNA replication during the S-phase of the cell cycle.

Group: Most Challenging Aspect & Study Plan

challengingConcept DNA replication in eukaryotes and prokaryotes differs in fundamental ways.
challengingConcept[comment] In prokaryotic cells, there is only one point of origin, replication occurs in two opposing directions at the same time, and takes place in the cell cytoplasm. Eukaryotic cells on the other hand, have multiple points of origin, and use unidirectional replication within the nucleus of the cell. Prokaryotic cells possess one or two types of polymerases, whereas eukaryotes have four or more. Replication also happens at a much faster rate in prokaryotic cells.In addition, eukaryotes also have a distinct process for replicating the telomeres at the ends of their chromosomes. With their circular chromosomes, prokaryotes have no ends to synthesize. Lastly, the short replication in prokaryotes occurs almost continuously, but eukaryotic cells only undergo DNA replication during the S-phase of the cell cycle.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Telomeres create a problem withreplication due to the fact that each time replication occurs the telomeres are actually shortened. This is eventually what leads to a "natural" death. I think it is interesting that something so key to the DNA replication process is actually what often proves to be the flaw in the DNA replication process.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] If certain chromosomes can be "specialized" and therefore distinguishable, it raises many questions about the way we observe all chromosomes. Can we mark any chromosome we want? How would this affect research and discovery?
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Since euchromatin is very lightly packed and heterochromatin is very thightly packed it makes for several potential combinations of the two. When studying epigenetics this becomes very important because those genetic markers come in and either tighten or loosen these holds.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Knowing that there are so many differences between eukaryotes and prokaryotes it makes sense that the DNA replication process is also different. DNA is the fundamental blueprint of an organism, and since the processess are different for these two different groups, they are therefore fundamentally different.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] As DNA polymerase alone cannot replicate the ends of chromosomes, telomerase aids in their replication and prevents chromosome degradation.
explainConcepts[SQ002] many of the cells of certain fly larvae grow to an enormous size through multiple cycles of DNA synthesis without cell division. The resulting giant cells contain as much as several thousand times the normal DNA complement.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Facultative heterochromatin is the result of genes that are silenced through a mechanism such as histone deacetylation or piRNA through RNAi. It is not repetitive and shares the compact structure of constitutive heterochromatin. However, under specific developmental or environmental signaling cues, it can lose its condensed structure and become transcriptionally active
phenomenonA Specialized Drosophila chromosomes allowed the identification of gene locations.
phenomenonA[comment] Cells with more than the normal DNA complement are said to be polyploid when they contain increased numbers of standard chromosomes. In several types of secretory cells of fly larvae, however, all the homologous chromosome copies are held side by side, like drinking straws in a box, creating a single polytene chromosome.
phenomenonB Specialized Drosophila chromosomes allowed the identification of gene locations.
phenomenonB[comment] Polytene chromosomes are often easy to see in the light microscope because they are so large and because the precisely aligned side-by-side adherence of individual chromatin strands greatly elongates the chromosome axis and prevents tangling. Politely has been most studied in the salivary gland cells of Drosophila larvae, in which the DNA in each of the four Drosophila chromosomes has been replicated through 10 cycles without separation of the daughter chromosomes.
